<subSubSection lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="250" pageId="4" pageNumber="249" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,1623,2008]" pageId="4" pageNumber="249">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,1623,1648]" pageId="4" pageNumber="249">Comments.</emphasis>
The form of the paranota in 
<taxonomicName authority="Recuero &amp; Sánchez-Vialas, 2018" authorityName="Recuero &amp; Sánchez-Vialas" authorityYear="2018" box="[688,958,1623,1648]" class="Diplopoda" family="Platyrhacidae" genus="Barydesmus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polydesmida" pageId="4" pageNumber="249" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nangaritza" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[688,958,1623,1648]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="249">Barydesmus nangaritza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[969,1063,1623,1648]" pageId="4" pageNumber="249" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[969,1063,1623,1648]" pageId="4" pageNumber="249">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
is unique among the American 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pocock" authorityYear="1895" box="[151,307,1659,1684]" class="Diplopoda" family="Platyrhacidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polydesmida" pageId="4" pageNumber="249" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Platyrhacidae</taxonomicName>
. Checking all descriptions and published figures, only 
<taxonomicName authority="(Cook, 1896 a)" authorityName="Recuero &amp; Sánchez-Vialas" authorityYear="2018" baseAuthorityName="Cook" baseAuthorityYear="1896" box="[922,1293,1659,1684]" class="Diplopoda" family="Platyrhacidae" genus="Barydesmus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polydesmida" pageId="4" pageNumber="249" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="exsul">
<emphasis box="[922,1123,1659,1684]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="249">Barydesmus exsul</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation box="[1138,1284,1659,1684]" pageId="4" pageNumber="249" refId="ref15722" refString="Cook, O. F. (1896 a) New american Platyrhacidae. Brandtia, 12, 51 - 54." type="journal article">Cook, 1896a</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
leaves some doubt about its possible similarity to the paranota of 
<taxonomicName authority="Recuero &amp; Sánchez-Vialas, 2018" authorityName="Recuero &amp; Sánchez-Vialas" authorityYear="2018" box="[743,896,1696,1719]" class="Diplopoda" family="Platyrhacidae" genus="Barydesmus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polydesmida" pageId="4" pageNumber="249" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nangaritza" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[743,896,1696,1719]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="249">B. nangaritza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[903,993,1695,1720]" pageId="4" pageNumber="249" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[903,993,1695,1720]" pageId="4" pageNumber="249">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
, as in the original description it is said: &quot;lateral carinae usually deeply excised opposite to the pore&quot; (
<bibRefCitation box="[840,1026,1731,1756]" pageId="4" pageNumber="249" refId="ref15722" refString="Cook, O. F. (1896 a) New american Platyrhacidae. Brandtia, 12, 51 - 54." type="journal article">Cook 1896a: 54</bibRefCitation>
). We have examined photographs of the 
<typeStatus box="[192,240,1768,1792]" pageId="4" pageNumber="249">type</typeStatus>
specimen of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Recuero &amp; Sánchez-Vialas" authorityYear="2018" baseAuthorityName="Cook" baseAuthorityYear="1896" box="[389,478,1767,1792]" class="Diplopoda" family="Platyrhacidae" genus="Barydesmus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polydesmida" pageId="4" pageNumber="249" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="exsul">
<emphasis box="[389,478,1767,1792]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="249">B. exsul</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the form of the paranota is highly variable among segments. Only paranota 5 and 12 appear clearly excised opposite to the pore (even if not as deeply as in 
<taxonomicName authority="Recuero &amp; Sánchez-Vialas, 2018" authorityName="Recuero &amp; Sánchez-Vialas" authorityYear="2018" box="[967,1119,1804,1827]" class="Diplopoda" family="Platyrhacidae" genus="Barydesmus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polydesmida" pageId="4" pageNumber="249" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nangaritza" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[967,1119,1804,1827]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="249">B. nangaritza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1125,1214,1803,1828]" pageId="4" pageNumber="249" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1125,1214,1803,1828]" pageId="4" pageNumber="249">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
), but most paranota of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Recuero &amp; Sánchez-Vialas" authorityYear="2018" baseAuthorityName="Cook" baseAuthorityYear="1896" box="[182,271,1839,1864]" class="Diplopoda" family="Platyrhacidae" genus="Barydesmus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polydesmida" pageId="4" pageNumber="249" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="exsul">
<emphasis box="[182,271,1839,1864]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="249">B. exsul</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have 3–4 blunt teeth providing the rough, irregular external margins typical of several other species of the family. Gonopod structure among 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cook" authorityYear="1896" box="[585,722,1875,1900]" class="Diplopoda" family="Platyrhacidae" genus="Barydesmus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polydesmida" pageId="4" pageNumber="249" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[585,722,1875,1900]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="249">Barydesmus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species, as in other 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pocock" authorityYear="1895" box="[956,1111,1875,1900]" class="Diplopoda" family="Platyrhacidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polydesmida" pageId="4" pageNumber="249" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Platyrhacidae</taxonomicName>
, is highly homogeneous and peripheral characters should be considered as major diagnostic features in this group (
<bibRefCitation box="[1183,1431,1911,1936]" pageId="4" pageNumber="249" refId="ref16434" refString="Hoffman, R. L., Martinez-Torres, D. &amp; Florez D., E. (2011) A new Colombian species in the milliped genus Psammodesmus, symbiotic host for bryophytes (Polydesmida: Platyrhacidae). Zootaxa, 3015, 52 - 60." type="journal article">
Hoffman 
<emphasis box="[1298,1353,1911,1936]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="249">et al</emphasis>
. 2011
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation box="[151,402,1947,1972]" pageId="4" pageNumber="249" refId="ref17075" refString="Martinez-Torres, D. (2016) Revision taxonomica y distribucion geografica de los milpies del genero Psammodesmus Cook, 1896 (Diplopoda: Polydesmida: Platyrhacidae). MSc Thesis in Biology, Universidad Nacional de Colombia, Facultad de Ciencias, Departamento de Biologia, Bogota D. C., Colombia, pp. 1 - 182." type="book chapter">Martínez-Torres 2016</bibRefCitation>
). Given the available information, it is not feasible to postulate solid hypotheses regarding the affinities among species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cook" authorityYear="1896" box="[499,636,1983,2008]" class="Diplopoda" family="Platyrhacidae" genus="Barydesmus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polydesmida" pageId="4" pageNumber="249" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[499,636,1983,2008]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="249">Barydesmus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
without a full review of the genus.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,151,501]" pageId="5" pageNumber="250">
<taxonomicName authority="Recuero &amp; Sánchez-Vialas, 2018" authorityName="Recuero &amp; Sánchez-Vialas" authorityYear="2018" box="[199,464,151,176]" class="Diplopoda" family="Platyrhacidae" genus="Barydesmus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polydesmida" pageId="5" pageNumber="250" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nangaritza" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[199,464,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="250">Barydesmus nangaritza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[470,559,151,176]" pageId="5" pageNumber="250" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[470,559,151,176]" pageId="5" pageNumber="250">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
comes from the Nangaritza River Basin, an area characterized by the presence of isolated sandstone mountains named &quot;tepuyes&quot;, and a humid subtropical climate (
<bibRefCitation pageId="5" pageNumber="250" refId="ref16017" refString="Guayasamin, J. M. &amp; Bonaccorso, E. (Eds.) (2011) Evaluacion ecologica rapida de la biodiversidad de los Tepuyes de la Cuenca Alta del Rio Nangaritza, Cordillera del Condor, Ecuador. Conservacion Internacional, Quito, pp. 1 - 135." type="book chapter">Guayasamín and Bonaccorso 2011</bibRefCitation>
). The habitat has a sandy soil covered by a thin layer of leaf litter, with dispersed stones and rotten logs. Most trees are covered with dense epiphytic vegetation. The 
<typeStatus box="[758,854,260,285]" pageId="5" pageNumber="250">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Recuero &amp; Sánchez-Vialas" authorityYear="2018" box="[891,1041,261,284]" class="Diplopoda" family="Platyrhacidae" genus="Barydesmus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polydesmida" pageId="5" pageNumber="250" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nangaritza">
<emphasis box="[891,1041,261,284]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="250">B. nangaritza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was found active by night, walking on a vertical trunk of a living tree, in a dense piedmont forest located on the eastern slope of a tepuy (
<figureCitation box="[1257,1321,295,320]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,992,1014]" captionTargetBox="[156,1436,195,968]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,195,968]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Location of the type locality of Barydesmus nangaritza sp. nov. and view of the habitat." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1453227/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="250">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,151,501]" pageId="5" pageNumber="250">
The biodiversity in this region has remained largely unexplored for a long time. Recent investigations, focused on regional diversity, have resulted in the description of at least four species of Amphibia, one of Reptilia, 10 of Phasmida and 13 of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Guayasamin and Bonaccorso 2011)" authorityName="Guayasamin and Bonaccorso" authorityYear="2011" baseAuthorityName="Guayasamin and Bonaccorso" baseAuthorityYear="2011" box="[399,983,404,429]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="250" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">
Tettigoniidae (
<bibRefCitation box="[565,975,404,429]" pageId="5" pageNumber="250" refId="ref16017" refString="Guayasamin, J. M. &amp; Bonaccorso, E. (Eds.) (2011) Evaluacion ecologica rapida de la biodiversidad de los Tepuyes de la Cuenca Alta del Rio Nangaritza, Cordillera del Condor, Ecuador. Conservacion Internacional, Quito, pp. 1 - 135." type="book chapter">Guayasamín and Bonaccorso 2011</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. This suggests that more effort is still needed to attain a better knowledge of the biodiversity and biological history of this remarkable region and its unique geological formations.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
